  "text": "Endurance will be assessed with the single leg heel-rise test. This test is a reliable measure of endurance in patients after ATR [CITATION_1] . With this test patients are instructed to stand on one foot on a 60 degree incline board and perform as many heel-rises as possible. Figure 1 shows the heel-rise test setup. Patients are allowed to have 2 fingertips per hand against the wall for balance, and will perform the rises at a rate of 30 heel rises per minute as guided by a metronome. For each heel-rise they are instructed to go as high as possible and then lower the heel to the starting position. The test will be terminated when the patients stop, cannot maintain the frequency, or cannot perform a proper heel rise [CITATION_2] . The heel-rise count of the injured foot will be compared to the contralateral (uninjured) foot. The outcome is calculated as the percentage of the heel-rise test count of the ATR-affected side compared to the contralateral (uninjured) limb. The unaffected side is evaluated first.",
